00:38:08.420 --> 00:38:12.820
They're sent away to a juvenile
detention center to do time.

00:38:12.820 --> 00:38:15.690
And it's almost like
their entire old life

00:38:15.690 --> 00:38:16.420
has disappeared.

00:38:16.420 --> 00:38:17.700
Who they were has disappeared.

00:38:17.700 --> 00:38:21.010
And a lot of the thought
of these prisoners as

00:38:21.010 --> 00:38:23.450
what is my life when I get out?

00:38:23.450 --> 00:38:25.560
What is my life
after I do my time?

00:38:25.560 --> 00:38:29.960
Is this mark ever-- is this
still on me for forever?

00:38:29.960 --> 00:38:31.120
So there's a lot of that.

00:38:31.120 --> 00:38:34.390
And then there's also
sometimes in my writing,

00:38:34.390 --> 00:38:37.380
I like to play with magical
realism and fantastical things.

00:38:37.380 --> 00:38:40.820
And the disappearing
can be quite literal.

00:38:40.820 --> 00:38:45.450
People actually can disappear
and have in my books.

00:38:45.450 --> 00:38:47.883
I won't give anymore away.

00:38:47.883 --> 00:38:50.992
AUDIENCE: Is there an author
whose career or body of work

00:38:50.992 --> 00:38:52.860
you'd like yours to
look like [INAUDIBLE]?

00:38:52.860 --> 00:38:53.610
NOVA REN SUMA: Oh!

00:38:56.930 --> 00:38:58.710
I'm just going to be
honest and say this

00:38:58.710 --> 00:39:01.030
even though she's a friend.

00:39:01.030 --> 00:39:05.330
I greatly admire the
[INAUDIBLE] author, Libba Bray.

00:39:05.330 --> 00:39:10.920
And what I admire about Libba
is she's so incredibly talented

00:39:10.920 --> 00:39:13.590
with the range of her work.

00:39:13.590 --> 00:39:16.990
So she has written
historical fantasy.

00:39:16.990 --> 00:39:19.220
Her latest series,
"The Diviners,"

00:39:19.220 --> 00:39:22.600
is 1920s New York, with
the occult, and politics,

00:39:22.600 --> 00:39:26.590
and sweeping epic stories,
as well as satire,

00:39:26.590 --> 00:39:29.830
and funny things,
and first person

00:39:29.830 --> 00:39:31.550
beautiful voice-y things.

00:39:31.550 --> 00:39:35.700
And I look at her, and I think,
if only I could find a way

00:39:35.700 --> 00:39:38.150
to have that kind of
range as a writer,

00:39:38.150 --> 00:39:40.570
and to be able to explore
everything so honestly,

00:39:40.570 --> 00:39:42.000
where it still feels like me.

00:39:42.000 --> 00:39:43.660
In every book, that's different.

00:39:43.660 --> 00:39:44.860
And I admire that so much.

00:39:44.860 --> 00:39:47.620
But I also admire how
she carries herself

00:39:47.620 --> 00:39:51.150
in this industry, how helpful
she is to fellow writers,

00:39:51.150 --> 00:39:55.070
and how wonderful she is with
her fans, and how open she is.

00:39:55.070 --> 00:39:58.250
And so I very much
think I would love

00:39:58.250 --> 00:40:03.060
to find a way to build a
career like Libba's one day

00:40:03.060 --> 00:40:07.345
and to have published the kind
of books that she publishes.

00:40:07.345 --> 00:40:10.315
AUDIENCE: I think yours is
off to more than a good start.

00:40:10.315 --> 00:40:13.285
Just going back to
"The Walls Around Us,"

00:40:13.285 --> 00:40:16.750
was there a reason why you
chose Stravinsky's "Firebird"

00:40:16.750 --> 00:40:19.029
as the ballet?

00:40:19.029 --> 00:40:19.820
NOVA REN SUMA: Yes.

00:40:19.820 --> 00:40:24.840
So in the story,
Violet is, in the past,

00:40:24.840 --> 00:40:27.870
they were performing the
"Firebird" as the summer

00:40:27.870 --> 00:40:29.110
showcase ballet.

00:40:29.110 --> 00:40:31.240
And Ori, her best
friend, was cast

00:40:31.240 --> 00:40:34.030
in the important starring
role of the firebird, which

00:40:34.030 --> 00:40:39.100
was the best role that Violet
wanted, and she didn't get.

00:40:39.100 --> 00:40:43.420
So for me, sometimes, this
book, I will tell you,

00:40:43.420 --> 00:40:44.790
is complete fiction.

00:40:44.790 --> 00:40:47.940
I was never in a juvenile
detention center.

00:40:47.940 --> 00:40:50.170
I am not a ghost.

00:40:50.170 --> 00:40:51.650
This is completely made up.

00:40:51.650 --> 00:40:55.010
But things from my real
life do end up in my books.

00:40:55.010 --> 00:40:58.400
And so the ballet stuff
is from real life.

00:40:58.400 --> 00:41:02.690
I studied ballet from when
I was 4 to when I was 16.

00:41:02.690 --> 00:41:03.990
I was not very good.

00:41:03.990 --> 00:41:06.950
I never would have been a
professional like Violet

00:41:06.950 --> 00:41:08.000
in this story.

00:41:08.000 --> 00:41:11.480
But it was just so
much a part of my life

00:41:11.480 --> 00:41:14.280
going to ballet class after
school, going on the weekends,

00:41:14.280 --> 00:41:16.250
doing performances like this.

00:41:16.250 --> 00:41:20.850
And the last performance that I
did before I quit ballet to go

00:41:20.850 --> 00:41:24.630
hang out with my friends and go
to parties, which is the truth.

00:41:24.630 --> 00:41:27.550
That's what happened, the last
ballet that I performed in

00:41:27.550 --> 00:41:30.530
was "The Firebird,"
and I was one

00:41:30.530 --> 00:41:33.820
of the dancing maidens, which
is the role that Violet actually

00:41:33.820 --> 00:41:34.900
does get.

00:41:34.900 --> 00:41:39.330
And I remember I had a very
plain costume in comparison

00:41:39.330 --> 00:41:41.650
to the firebird's
costume, and we

00:41:41.650 --> 00:41:46.180
had little bean
bags, gold bean bags

00:41:46.180 --> 00:41:48.050
that we had to throw on stage.

00:41:48.050 --> 00:41:49.996
And this was the
greatest fear of mine,

00:41:49.996 --> 00:41:52.370
that I would not catch it when
it came to me, because I'm

00:41:52.370 --> 00:41:54.240
terrible at catching things.

00:41:54.240 --> 00:41:57.160
So it was just this
very vivid memory.

00:41:57.160 --> 00:41:59.590
But I remembered you
know the dancer who

00:41:59.590 --> 00:42:03.820
danced "The Firebird," and that
incredibly intense dancing,

00:42:03.820 --> 00:42:05.890
the incredibly intense solo.

00:42:05.890 --> 00:42:08.510
It was such a memorable
point in my life.

00:42:08.510 --> 00:42:11.970
And she was trapped.

00:42:11.970 --> 00:42:13.280
This character's trapped.

00:42:13.280 --> 00:42:16.300
And just that feeling felt
very connected to "The Walls

00:42:16.300 --> 00:42:17.070
Around Us."

00:42:17.070 --> 00:42:20.340
And also, at least the dancer
who was in the performance

00:42:20.340 --> 00:42:23.680
that I was in, there was this
anger that was all through her.

00:42:23.680 --> 00:42:26.340
And it just really
felt connected

00:42:26.340 --> 00:42:28.410
to when I wanted
to write this book.

00:42:28.410 --> 00:42:31.724
So when I knew Violet was going
to be a ballerina, of course,

00:42:31.724 --> 00:42:32.890
it had to be "The Firebird."

00:42:32.890 --> 00:42:35.240
It had to be with the
ballet that I remembered,

00:42:35.240 --> 00:42:41.050
the last one that I danced in,
but also, the story felt right.

00:42:41.050 --> 00:42:44.630
AUDIENCE: And if Amber, or
Violet, and Ori were boys,

00:42:44.630 --> 00:42:47.000
how do you think your
story would be different?

00:42:47.000 --> 00:42:49.260
NOVA REN SUMA: That is such
an interesting question.

00:42:49.260 --> 00:42:49.780
It's funny.

00:42:49.780 --> 00:42:55.180
I most exclusively write about
teenage girls and about girls.

00:42:55.180 --> 00:42:59.550
And I can't even imagine
what it would be like

00:42:59.550 --> 00:43:02.050
for me to write this
story about three boys

00:43:02.050 --> 00:43:03.740
in a juvenile detention center.

00:43:03.740 --> 00:43:06.970
And I think maybe--
clearly, that's a story

00:43:06.970 --> 00:43:08.200
that I would love to read.

00:43:08.200 --> 00:43:09.860
That's a story
that another writer

00:43:09.860 --> 00:43:12.260
would be able to make
so vivid and wonderful.

00:43:12.260 --> 00:43:14.220
But for me, so
much of my writing

00:43:14.220 --> 00:43:16.340
is about writing about
the experience of being

00:43:16.340 --> 00:43:22.240
a teenage girl and all kinds of
girls, exploring all avenues.

00:43:22.240 --> 00:43:25.590
And so I can't even
fathom how that book

00:43:25.590 --> 00:43:27.160
would be if written by me.

00:43:27.160 --> 00:43:28.820
So I'm intrigued
by the question,

00:43:28.820 --> 00:43:30.800
but I don't even know.

00:43:30.800 --> 00:43:33.050
I feel like it would
be not a book by me.

00:43:33.050 --> 00:43:35.490
It would be another
worthy book, but not

00:43:35.490 --> 00:43:37.430
something that I would
be able to do justice.

00:43:37.430 --> 00:43:39.263
AUDIENCE: Well, and
also, knowing the prison

00:43:39.263 --> 00:43:41.190
dynamics would be very
different, and also,

00:43:41.190 --> 00:43:42.869
[INAUDIBLE] competitive
dance world.

00:43:42.869 --> 00:43:43.660
NOVA REN SUMA: Yes.

00:43:43.660 --> 00:43:44.990
The ballet stuff
would be different.

00:43:44.990 --> 00:43:46.656
And there's something
really interesting

00:43:46.656 --> 00:43:51.660
to explore with female
friendship, and enemies,

00:43:51.660 --> 00:43:53.740
and friends, and how that
can be the same thing.

00:43:53.740 --> 00:43:55.590
That can be the same person.

00:43:55.590 --> 00:43:59.760
And friendship with guys
is probably different,

00:43:59.760 --> 00:44:03.180
but there's something really
interesting with girls.

00:44:03.180 --> 00:44:06.365
And there's the girls
in the prison, locked up

00:44:06.365 --> 00:44:08.740
in the prison, and there's
the girls in the dance school.

00:44:08.740 --> 00:44:11.090
And the girls in the dance
school are just as vicious

00:44:11.090 --> 00:44:14.495
and mean as the
girls in the prison.

00:44:14.495 --> 00:44:16.244
AUDIENCE: That's a
"Black Swan" reference.

00:44:16.244 --> 00:44:18.735
NOVA REN SUMA: [LAUGHING] Yeah.

00:44:18.735 --> 00:44:20.735
AUDIENCE: And so here's
a metaphysical question.

00:44:20.735 --> 00:44:23.686
What are your thoughts on karma,
regret, and how supernatural

00:44:23.686 --> 00:44:24.727
[? would get involved? ?]

00:44:27.932 --> 00:44:29.640
NOVA REN SUMA: I find
that a lot of times

00:44:29.640 --> 00:44:32.470
when I'm writing these
fantastical stories, there

00:44:32.470 --> 00:44:36.050
always is some kind
of karmic retribution.

00:44:36.050 --> 00:44:41.090
Like if somebody does something
magical or has a power,

00:44:41.090 --> 00:44:44.720
there's always some
consequence for that.

00:44:44.720 --> 00:44:47.260
In the worlds that I create,
I can't imagine there not

00:44:47.260 --> 00:44:48.910
being some
consequence, something

00:44:48.910 --> 00:44:50.660
that you do that you're
not allowed to do,

00:44:50.660 --> 00:44:53.390
that then you have to pay for.

00:44:53.390 --> 00:44:56.720
So I think that
kind of philosophy

00:44:56.720 --> 00:44:59.110
has seeped its
way into my books,

00:44:59.110 --> 00:45:03.550
and so when I imagine
something completely fantastic,

00:45:03.550 --> 00:45:06.010
and strange, and
in another world,

00:45:06.010 --> 00:45:08.490
I'm thinking of that rule.

00:45:08.490 --> 00:45:10.570
And that's come
through in my book,

00:45:10.570 --> 00:45:14.050
"Imaginary Girls," and I think
here in "The Walls Around Us,"

00:45:14.050 --> 00:45:17.840
there's that feeling
of who deserves what,

00:45:17.840 --> 00:45:20.390
and what happens when
someone who doesn't deserve

00:45:20.390 --> 00:45:23.610
it starts getting a lot, getting
all the good things happening

00:45:23.610 --> 00:45:25.990
to her, is that really
going to come through?

00:45:25.990 --> 00:45:28.470
And in real life, we
know that a lot of times

00:45:28.470 --> 00:45:30.740
there's no retribution,
and terrible people

00:45:30.740 --> 00:45:32.450
get wonderful things.

00:45:32.450 --> 00:45:35.070
But maybe in
fiction, I have a way

00:45:35.070 --> 00:45:37.748
of correcting that a little bit.

00:45:37.748 --> 00:45:40.682
AUDIENCE: To cosmic justice.

00:45:40.682 --> 00:45:43.616
And so I think a number of
us are a little more extreme

00:45:43.616 --> 00:45:47.039
in saying we're curious to
hear more about this launch pad

00:45:47.039 --> 00:45:48.995
workshop that you attended.

00:45:48.995 --> 00:45:51.195
It's not often that
you hear about writers

00:45:51.195 --> 00:45:53.010
going to a workshop
that's funded by NASA--

00:45:53.010 --> 00:45:53.885
NOVA REN SUMA: Right.

00:45:53.885 --> 00:45:55.352
AUDIENCE: --astronomy.

00:45:55.352 --> 00:45:57.063
What was your experience
like from that,

00:45:57.063 --> 00:45:58.775
and what did you
take away from it?

00:45:58.775 --> 00:46:00.280
And how has it
influenced your work?

00:46:00.280 --> 00:46:02.488
NOVA REN SUMA: Well, I should
say that the Launch Pad

00:46:02.488 --> 00:46:04.860
Astronomy Workshop is at
the University of Wyoming

00:46:04.860 --> 00:46:06.090
every summer.

00:46:06.090 --> 00:46:10.450
And it's open to writers who
are interested in bringing

00:46:10.450 --> 00:46:13.320
in some science into their
writing, specifically

00:46:13.320 --> 00:46:14.220
astronomy.

00:46:14.220 --> 00:46:17.090
So you don't have to be
a science fiction writer.

00:46:17.090 --> 00:46:19.140
You don't have to
be a science writer.

00:46:19.140 --> 00:46:21.530
I'm a YA writer who
writes magical things.

00:46:21.530 --> 00:46:25.680
But I had a book in
mind that's still

00:46:25.680 --> 00:46:31.700
in progress about an astronaut,
and I needed more basis

00:46:31.700 --> 00:46:34.780
to make sure I wasn't
making terrible mistakes,

00:46:34.780 --> 00:46:36.470
but also, inspiration.

00:46:36.470 --> 00:46:39.700
And so I was really
excited to apply and get

00:46:39.700 --> 00:46:41.260
the funding to go.

00:46:41.260 --> 00:46:44.760
And every year, I think it's
funded from different places.

00:46:44.760 --> 00:46:46.550
So the year I went,
it was funded by NASA.

00:46:46.550 --> 00:46:49.530
I don't know who's funding
it for the next summer.

00:46:49.530 --> 00:46:50.200
So I went.

00:46:50.200 --> 00:46:56.200
And really, what it is is
an intense, week long class

00:46:56.200 --> 00:47:00.360
on astronomy, like intense, like
hours of learning astronomy.

00:47:00.360 --> 00:47:04.240
And if you've taken an
astronomy college course before,

00:47:04.240 --> 00:47:06.760
some of it might be
an old hat to you.

00:47:06.760 --> 00:47:08.140
For me, it was all new.

00:47:08.140 --> 00:47:10.300
I hadn't taken
astronomy in college,

00:47:10.300 --> 00:47:12.380
and so I had a lot to learn.

00:47:12.380 --> 00:47:15.050
But at the same time,
we moved past the basics

00:47:15.050 --> 00:47:18.760
and into a lot of what ifs
with terraforming Mars,

00:47:18.760 --> 00:47:21.180
or all these really
interesting ideas.

00:47:21.180 --> 00:47:23.680
And I learned so much.

00:47:23.680 --> 00:47:26.990
I filled up notebooks
full of notes.

00:47:26.990 --> 00:47:30.890
Also, you're with a
group of a fellow writers

00:47:30.890 --> 00:47:33.970
from different genres-- science
fiction and fantasy writers,

00:47:33.970 --> 00:47:38.180
and there were some YA writers,
and just short story writers.

00:47:38.180 --> 00:47:41.990
And we really bonded and
connected while we were there.

00:47:41.990 --> 00:47:44.950
And there were also some
visits to a telescope

00:47:44.950 --> 00:47:49.410
to see the stars, and so it was
a really, really interesting

00:47:49.410 --> 00:47:49.910
week.

00:47:49.910 --> 00:47:51.780
And if that anyone
is listening to this

00:47:51.780 --> 00:47:53.320
and thinks that's
interesting, there

00:47:53.320 --> 00:47:54.890
should be another
one next summer.

00:47:54.890 --> 00:47:57.030
And I think the applications
open in the winter.

00:47:59.976 --> 00:48:02.922
AUDIENCE: And we'll open it up
to questions from the audience.

00:48:09.603 --> 00:48:11.269
MALE SPEAKER: Well,
I was going to say--

00:48:11.269 --> 00:48:14.706
so she said that [INAUDIBLE]
got a chance [? to read it. ?]

00:48:14.706 --> 00:48:15.688
I just picked it up.

00:48:15.688 --> 00:48:16.896
NOVA REN SUMA: Oh, thank you.

00:48:16.896 --> 00:48:19.719
MALE SPEAKER: She said
about how you write so well.

00:48:19.719 --> 00:48:22.260
You develop the other characters
in the prison and everything

00:48:22.260 --> 00:48:22.759
so well.

00:48:22.759 --> 00:48:26.069
If you could, is there
anybody in particular

00:48:26.069 --> 00:48:28.230
that you [INAUDIBLE]
side [INAUDIBLE]

00:48:28.230 --> 00:48:32.760
that you would really love to go
on a tangent with, if you have?

00:48:32.760 --> 00:48:34.760
NOVA REN SUMA: Well, you
know what's interesting

00:48:34.760 --> 00:48:38.110
about this book is there's
this main, central figure

00:48:38.110 --> 00:48:41.030
in this book called
Ori Orianna who doesn't

00:48:41.030 --> 00:48:43.110
get her own perspective.

00:48:43.110 --> 00:48:46.235
And her story is told through
the eyes of Amber, who's

00:48:46.235 --> 00:48:48.360
her cell mate, and then
through the eyes of Violet,

00:48:48.360 --> 00:48:50.300
who was her former best friend.

00:48:50.300 --> 00:48:53.091
And so you piece together
this portrait of her

00:48:53.091 --> 00:48:55.090
through other people's
eyes, which I always find

00:48:55.090 --> 00:48:56.510
so fascinating, as a reader.

00:48:56.510 --> 00:48:58.240
I love that kind of
stuff in the story.

00:48:58.240 --> 00:49:01.070
But then it leaves why
did I not tell the story

00:49:01.070 --> 00:49:02.280
from Ori's prospective?

00:49:02.280 --> 00:49:04.010
A lot of readers
have asked me, why

00:49:04.010 --> 00:49:06.240
is there not Ori's perspective?

00:49:06.240 --> 00:49:09.860
And there was one
point where I was like,

00:49:09.860 --> 00:49:11.236
should I have letters from her?

00:49:11.236 --> 00:49:12.860
Should I add some of
that in the story?

00:49:12.860 --> 00:49:15.720
I even think I tried, and
I couldn't find her voice.

00:49:15.720 --> 00:49:20.950
So I think I would try a more
secondary character, someone

00:49:20.950 --> 00:49:24.410
that nobody would expect.

00:49:24.410 --> 00:49:29.740
There's a girl who is an
outcast and eats her own hair.

00:49:29.740 --> 00:49:30.760
Her name is Kennedy.

00:49:30.760 --> 00:49:33.160
She might be
interesting to explore.

00:49:33.160 --> 00:49:37.430
There's a girl who's
surreptitiously dealing drugs.

00:49:37.430 --> 00:49:38.470
Her name is Peaches.

00:49:38.470 --> 00:49:40.510
She might be
interesting to explore.

00:49:40.510 --> 00:49:44.280
I feel like anyone of them
might lead to something,

00:49:44.280 --> 00:49:46.800
but it would be a
whole separate story.

00:49:46.800 --> 00:49:51.070
It would be her story, and then
it would touch the other one.

00:49:51.070 --> 00:49:52.780
But it's interesting.

00:49:52.780 --> 00:49:55.280
There's a lot of
vivid possibility,

00:49:55.280 --> 00:49:58.550
if I ever wanted to write
something beyond this.

00:49:58.550 --> 00:50:01.280
But then again, my stories
are always standalone.

00:50:01.280 --> 00:50:04.410
They're meant to be
just what they are.

00:50:04.410 --> 00:50:06.840
Even if they leave
questions at the end,

00:50:06.840 --> 00:50:09.320
the reader is left to
ask those questions

00:50:09.320 --> 00:50:12.190
and determine the
answers on their own.

00:50:12.190 --> 00:50:13.315
Thank you for the question.

00:50:16.490 --> 00:50:18.070
It looks like we're
up [? time. ?]

00:50:18.070 --> 00:50:18.670
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:50:18.670 --> 00:50:20.170
Thank you so much for coming in.

